Exiftool commands:

Read all metadata:
exiftool filename.jpg

To read metadata from multiple files:
exiftool a.jpg b.jpg

To read metadata from all files in a directory:
exiftool dir_name

Read specific tags:
exiftool -Tag1 -Tag2 filename.jpg
Example: exiftool -ImageSize -ExposureTime b.jpg

Write or modify a tag:
exiftool -TAG=VALUE filename.jpg
Example: exiftool -artist="Phil Harvey" a.jpg
By default, the original file is preserved with _original appended to its name.

Delete a tag:
exiftool -TAG= filename.jpg
Example: exiftool -comment= a.jpg

Delete all metadata:
exiftool -all= filename.jpg 

Advanced Commands
Copy tags from one file to another:
exiftool -tagsFromFile src.jpg dst.jpg

Rename files based on a tag:
exiftool '-filename<CreateDate' -d %Y%m%d_%H%M%S.%%e dir
This command renames all files in the specified directory (dir) to a format like YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS.EXT using the CreateDate value.

Move or copy files into directories based on a tag:
exiftool -o . '-Directory<CreateDate' -d %Y/%m/ dir
This command copies files from dir into a directory hierarchy based on the year and month of the CreateDate (e.g., ./2024/03/). The -o . ensures files are copied, not moved, and the original file extension is preserved.
